<subSubSection pageId="156" pageNumber="156" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="156" pageNumber="156">
13. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:143925" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pseudomyrma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pseudomyrma phyllophila Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="156" pageNumber="156" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phyllophila">Pseudomyrma phyllophila</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="156" pageNumber="156" type="description">
<paragraph lastPageNumber="157" pageId="156" pageNumber="156">Worker. Length 2 2/3 lines.-Obscure rufo-testaceous: the head and prothorax of the brightest colour; the antennae, face anteriorly, mandibles, anterior tibiae, the tarsi and articulations of the legs, pale testaceous; the antennae dusky towards the apex. Abdomen ovate, pointed at the apex, covered with fine silky pile; the first node of the abdomen clavate, the petiole short and thick, with a minute acute tooth at the base beneath, the sides of the node flattened; the second node much wider and subglobose.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="157" pageNumber="157" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="157" pageNumber="157">
<pageBreakToken pageId="157" pageNumber="157" start="start">Hab</pageBreakToken>
. Rio (Constantia). (Coll. Rev. Hamlet Clark.)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="157" pageNumber="157" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="157" pageNumber="157">
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:143870" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pseudomyrma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pseudomyrma sericata Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="157" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sericata">P. sericata</taxonomicName>
, but in that species the petiole is longer and very slender, and not toothed beneath.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
